091Sm 30:9 So David and his 600 men set out, and they came to the brook Besor.
091Sm 30:10 But 200 of the men were too exhausted to cross the brook, so David continued the pursuit with 400 men.
091Sm 30:11 Along the way they found an Egyptian man in a field and brought him to David. They gave him some bread to eat and water to drink.
091Sm 30:12 They also gave him part of a fig cake and two clusters of raisins, for he hadn't had anything to eat or drink for three days and nights. Before long his strength returned.
091Sm 30:13 "To whom do you belong, and where do you come from?" David asked him. "I am an Egyptian - the slave of an Amalekite," he replied. "My master abandoned me three days ago because I was sick.
091Sm 30:14 We were on our way back from raiding the Kerethites in the Negev, the territory of Judah, and the land of Caleb, and we had just burned Ziklag."
091Sm 30:15 "Will you lead me to this band of raiders?" David asked. The young man replied, "If you take an oath in God's name that you will not kill me or give me back to my master, then I will guide you to them."
091Sm 30:16 So he led David to them, and they found the Amalekites spread out across the fields, eating and drinking and dancing with joy because of the vast amount of plunder they had taken from the Philistines and the land of Judah.
091Sm 30:17 David and his men rushed in among them and slaughtered them throughout that night and the entire next day until evening. None of the Amalekites escaped except 400 young men who fled on camels.
091Sm 30:18 David got back everything the Amalekites had taken, and he rescued his two wives.
091Sm 30:19 Nothing was missing£º small or great, son or daughter, nor anything else that had been taken. David brought everything back.
091Sm 30:20 He also recovered all the flocks and herds, and his men drove them ahead of the other livestock. "This plunder belongs to David!" they said.
091Sm 30:21 Then David returned to the brook Besor and met up with the 200 men who had been left behind because they were too exhausted to go with him. They went out to meet David and his men, and David greeted them joyfully.
091Sm 30:22 But some evil troublemakers among David's men said, "They didn't go with us, so they can't have any of the plunder we recovered. Give them their wives and children, and tell them to be gone."
091Sm 30:23 But David said, "No, my brothers! Don't be selfish with what the LORD has given us. He has kept us safe and helped us defeat the band of raiders that attacked us.
091Sm 30:24 Who will listen when you talk like this? We share and share alike - those who go to battle and those who guard the equipment."
091Sm 30:25 From then on David made this a decree and regulation for Israel, and it is still followed today.
091Sm 30:26 When he arrived at Ziklag, David sent part of the plunder to the elders of Judah, who were his friends. "Here is a present for you, taken from the LORD's enemies," he said.
091Sm 30:27 The gifts were sent to the people of the following towns David had visited£º Bethel, Ramoth-negev, Jattir,
091Sm 30:28 Aroer, Siphmoth, Eshtemoa,
091Sm 30:29 Racal¨ç, the towns of the Jerahmeelites, the towns of the Kenites, / ¨ç{Greek version reads Carmel}
091Sm 30:30 Hormah, Bor-ashan, Athach,
091Sm 30:31 Hebron, and all the other places David and his men had visited.
091Sm 31:1 Now the Philistines attacked Israel, and the men of Israel fled before them. Many were slaughtered on the slopes of Mount Gilboa.
